{
  "family": "Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag Reaction (Remote Functionalization)",
  "candidate": {
    "substrate_smiles": [
      "CCCCN(C)Cl"
    ],
    "product_smiles": [
      "C1CCCN1C"
    ],
    "optional_reagent_smiles": [
      "O.O=S(=O)=O"
    ],
    "rationale": "This is a classic and simple textbook example of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. N-chloro-N-methylbutan-1-amine, upon treatment with acid (e.g., sulfuric acid) and then base, undergoes a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer via a nitrogen-centered radical. This is followed by radical recombination to form a C-Cl bond at the delta-position, and subsequent intramolecular nucleophilic substitution (S_N2) upon basification yields the N-methylpyrrolidine product. The substrate is a simple acyclic N-chloroamine, and the product is the characteristic five-membered pyrrolidine ring.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The core transformation is the formation of a pyrrolidine from an N-haloamine via a 1,5-hydrogen atom transfer. This specific intramolecular C-H amination is characteristic of the Hofmann-Löffler-Freytag reaction. The use of a simple, acyclic N-chloroamine substrate avoids overlap with more complex alkaloid syntheses or other named reactions involving different functional groups or ring systems. It specifically avoids arenes, diazo compounds, and other motifs that could cause collisions with unrelated radical or cyclization reactions."
  }
}
